# Guiding Principles

## Single Source of Truth

The backend owns all simulation state.

The frontend should never duplicate or independently calculate simulation behavior.

Examples include:

* vehicle movement
* routing
* demand generation
* traffic lights
* scheduling
* lane changes
* building state

The frontend only visualizes this information.

---

## Preserve Existing Layering

Current layering should remain intact.

```
Browser

↓

API

↓

Simulation

↓

Lane Graph

↓

Geometry

↓

Data
```

No frontend code should directly manipulate simulation internals.

---

## Deterministic Simulation

Existing deterministic behavior must remain unchanged.

Identical maps and seeds should continue producing identical simulations.

This ensures:

* reproducible bugs
* reliable testing
* deterministic save files

---

# Backend Responsibilities

The backend will become the simulation server.

Responsibilities include:

* maintaining the RoadNetwork
* executing simulation ticks
* routing vehicles
* generating traffic demand
* processing lane changes
* managing traffic lights
* loading maps
* saving maps
* validating editor operations
* maintaining undo history
* broadcasting simulation state

The backend remains responsible for every authoritative simulation decision.

---

# Frontend Responsibilities

The frontend will become a rendering and editing client.

Responsibilities include:

* drawing roads
* drawing buildings
* drawing vehicles
* camera movement
* selection
* toolbars
* inspector panels
* property editing
* sending editing commands
* interpolating between simulation snapshots for smooth rendering

The frontend should never perform simulation calculations.

---

# Communication Strategy

Two communication methods will be used.

## REST API

REST endpoints are appropriate for discrete user actions.

Examples include:

* create road
* delete road
* place building
* move node
* undo
* redo
* load map
* save map
* start simulation
* pause simulation
* stop simulation

These are request/response operations.

---

## WebSockets

WebSockets are appropriate for continuously changing information.

Examples include:

* vehicle positions
* simulation clock
* traffic lights
* performance statistics
* simulation status
* selected object updates

A persistent connection avoids repeatedly polling the backend.

---

# Rendering Strategy

Static map geometry should only be transmitted when necessary.

Examples include:

* roads
* buildings
* intersections
* lane geometry
* palettes

Dynamic simulation data should be streamed continuously.

Examples include:

* vehicle positions
* vehicle rotation
* vehicle speed
* traffic light states
* simulation clock

The frontend combines the static map with dynamic updates to render each frame.

---

