# Migration Phases

## Phase 1 — Complete Existing Refactor

Before introducing any web technologies, complete the existing refactor plan.

Priority:

* extract RoadNetwork
* extract geometry helpers
* extract renderer
* extract controller
* extract camera
* extract remaining UI panels

This removes the primary architectural bottleneck before introducing a second UI.

---

## Phase 2 — Headless Backend

Separate the simulation loop completely from Pygame.

The simulation should be executable without creating a window.

Expected result:

```
Simulation

↓

Update

↓

State
```

No rendering required.

---

## Phase 3 — Introduce FastAPI

Wrap the simulation with a web server.

Create API endpoints for:

* editing
* simulation control
* loading
* saving
* inspector access

No frontend changes are required at this stage.

---

## Phase 4 — Browser Renderer

Build an initial browser client.

Initially support:

* map rendering
* vehicle rendering
* camera movement

The Pygame editor continues to function during this phase.

---

## Phase 5 — Browser Editor

Gradually replace editor functionality.

Examples:

* selection
* node editing
* road drawing
* building placement
* inspector
* toolbar

Pygame remains available until feature parity is achieved.

---

## Phase 6 — Complete Migration

After all editor functionality has been migrated:

* remove Pygame rendering
* remove Pygame event handling
* retain the simulation engine

The simulator now runs entirely through the browser.

---

# Testing Strategy

Existing deterministic tests remain the primary verification mechanism.

Every migration step should preserve:

* deterministic generation
* save compatibility
* routing behavior
* scheduling
* lane changes
* traffic lights
* undo history

New API endpoints should receive automated tests where appropriate.

The simulation should remain executable headlessly throughout the migration.

---

# Long-Term Benefits

Completing this migration provides several advantages:

* Modern browser-based interface
* Platform-independent deployment
* Cleaner separation between simulation and presentation
* Easier future UI development
* Potential for collaborative editing
* Easier remote hosting
* Simpler integration with external tools
* Greater maintainability through stronger architectural boundaries

The simulation engine remains unchanged while the user experience becomes significantly more flexible and maintainable.
